{"title_page": "Inter arma enim silent leges", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{for|the Star Trek episode|Inter Arma Enim Silent Leges (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)}}\n\n'''''Inter arma enim silent l\u0113g\u0113s''''' is a [[List of Latin phrases|Latin phrase]] meaning \"For among [times of] arms, the laws fall mute,\" but it is more popularly rendered as \"In times of war, the law falls silent.\"\n\n==In Ancient Rome==\nThis [[aphorism]] was likely first written in these words by [[Cicero]] in his published oration ''[[Pro Milone]]'', but Cicero's actual wording was ''Silent enim l\u0113g\u0113s inter arma''. \n\nAt the time that Cicero used the phrase, [[riot|mob violence]] was common. Armed gangs led by partisan leaders controlled the streets of Rome; nevertheless such leaders were elected to high offices.\n\n==Posterity==\n\nAmongst other Latin writers [[Jerome]] uses the expression in Letter 126.\n\n==In the US==\n[[Abraham Lincoln]]'s request for an opinion on the suspension of the right to ''[[habeas corpus]]'' during the [[American Civil War]] resulted eventually in the following decision, in ''[[Ex parte Merryman]]'' (1861), of [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[Roger B. Taney]], as a judge of the [[United States circuit court]] for the [[United States federal judicial district|District]] of [[Maryland]]:\n\n{{quote|\n# That the president&nbsp;... cannot suspend the privilege of the writ of ''habeas corpus'', nor authorize a military officer to do it.\n# That a military officer has no right to arrest and detain a person not subject to the rules and articles of war&nbsp;... except in aid of the judicial authority, and subject to its control.}}\n\nThe United States' government explicitly referred to this maxim within its argument in the case ''[[Ex parte Milligan]]'', when it remarked (with an additional reference to Cicero) that \"these [amendments of the Bill of Rights], in truth, are all peace provisions of the Constitution and, like all other conventional and legislative laws and enactments, are silent amidst arms, and when [[salus populi suprema lex esto|the safety of the people becomes the supreme law]].\"\n\nThe erosion of citizens' rights during [[World War II]] were upheld in the Supreme Court case ''[[Hirabayashi v. United States]]'' (1943), which held that the application of curfews against members of a minority group were constitutional when the nation was at war with the country from which that group originated. ''[[Yasui v. United States]]'' was a companion case decided on the same day.\n\nIn its more modern usage, the phrase has become a watchword about the erosion of civil liberties during wartime. In the immediate wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], the maxim was aired and questioned in the [[media of the United States]], with renewed force. The implication of the saying, as currently used, is in debate whether civil liberties and freedoms are subservient to a wartime nation's duty of self-defense.  \n\nIn 1998 [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[William Rehnquist]], in ''All the Laws but One: Civil Liberties in Wartime'' suggested that \"the least justified of the curtailments of civil liberty\" were unlikely to be accepted by the courts in wars of the future: \"It is neither desirable nor is it remotely likely that civil liberty will occupy as favored a position in wartime as it does in peacetime. But it is both desirable and likely that more careful attention will be paid by the courts to the basis for the government's claims of necessity as a basis for curtailing civil liberty. ... The laws will thus not be silent in time of war, but they will speak with a somewhat different voice.\"\n\nIn 2004, [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Antonin Scalia]] used this phrase to decry the plurality decision in ''[[Hamdi v. Rumsfeld]]'' which, in his view, upheld the detention of a [[Citizenship of the United States|US citizen]] as an enemy combatant without charge or suspension of ''habeas corpus''.\n{{quote|Many think it not only inevitable but entirely proper that liberty give way to security in times of national crisis that, at the extremes of military exigency, ''inter arma silent leges''. Whatever the general merits of the view that war silences law or modulates its voice, that view has no place in the interpretation and application of a Constitution designed precisely to confront war and, in a manner that accords with democratic principles, to accommodate it.<ref>Antonin Scalia, [https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/03-6696.ZD.html dissenting opinion] in Hamdi v. Rumsfeld (2004).</ref>}}\n\n== In fiction ==\n\nThe phrase was used as the title for [[Inter Arma Enim Silent Leges (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|a 1999 episode]] of the science fiction TV series ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''. In it, the character [[List_of_recurring_Star_Trek:_Deep_Space_Nine_characters#Ross,_William_J.|Admiral Ross]] uses the phrase to justify an unethical act of espionage committed during [[Dominion War|a war]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[State of emergency]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/milo.shtml Cicero Pro Milone], at [[The Latin Library]]\n*[https://www.wired.com/news/politics/0,1283,47051,00.html Declan McCullogh, \"Why Liberty Suffers in Wartime\"], 24 September 2001\n*[http://www.suburbanchicagonews.com/focus/terrorism/archives/0901/e30civil.html Jerry Schwartz, AP, \"Will the law be silent in a time of crisis?\"] 30 September 2001\n\n[[Category:Brocards]]\n[[Category:Cicero]]\n[[Category:Latin political words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{for|the Star Trek episode|Inter Arma Enim Silent Leges (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)}}\n\n'''''Inter arma enim silent l\u0113g\u0113s''''' is a [[List of Latin phrases|Latin phrase]] meaning \"For among [times of] arms, the laws fall mute\", but it is more popularly rendered as \"In times of war, the law falls silent.\"\n\n==In Ancient Rome==\nThis [[aphorism]] was likely first written in these words by [[Cicero]] in his published oration ''[[Pro Milone]]'', but Cicero's actual wording was ''Silent enim l\u0113g\u0113s inter arma''. \n\nAt the time that Cicero used the phrase, [[riot|mob violence]] was common. Armed gangs led by partisan leaders controlled the streets of Rome; nevertheless such leaders were elected to high offices.\n\n==Posterity==\n\nAmongst other Latin writers [[Jerome]] uses the expression in Letter 126.\n\n==In the US==\n[[Abraham Lincoln]]'s request for an opinion on the suspension of the right to ''[[habeas corpus]]'' during the [[American Civil War]] resulted eventually in the following decision, in ''[[Ex parte Merryman]]'' (1861), of [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[Roger B. Taney]], as a judge of the [[United States circuit court]] for the [[United States federal judicial district|District]] of [[Maryland]]:\n\n{{quote|\n# That the president&nbsp;... cannot suspend the privilege of the writ of ''habeas corpus'', nor authorize a military officer to do it.\n# That a military officer has no right to arrest and detain a person not subject to the rules and articles of war&nbsp;... except in aid of the judicial authority, and subject to its control.}}\n\nThe United States' government explicitly referred to this maxim within its argument in the case ''[[Ex parte Milligan]]'', when it remarked (with an additional reference to Cicero) that \"these [amendments of the Bill of Rights], in truth, are all peace provisions of the Constitution and, like all other conventional and legislative laws and enactments, are silent amidst arms, and when [[salus populi suprema lex esto|the safety of the people becomes the supreme law]].\"\n\nThe erosion of citizens' rights during [[World War II]] were upheld in the Supreme Court case ''[[Hirabayashi v. United States]]'' (1943), which held that the application of curfews against members of a minority group were constitutional when the nation was at war with the country from which that group originated. ''[[Yasui v. United States]]'' was a companion case decided on the same day.\n\nIn its more modern usage, the phrase has become a watchword about the erosion of civil liberties during wartime. In the immediate wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], the maxim was aired and questioned in the [[media of the United States]], with renewed force. The implication of the saying, as currently used, is in debate whether civil liberties and freedoms are subservient to a wartime nation's duty of self-defense.  \n\nIn 1998 [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[William Rehnquist]], in ''All the Laws but One: Civil Liberties in Wartime'' suggested that \"the least justified of the curtailments of civil liberty\" were unlikely to be accepted by the courts in wars of the future: \"It is neither desirable nor is it remotely likely that civil liberty will occupy as favored a position in wartime as it does in peacetime. But it is both desirable and likely that more careful attention will be paid by the courts to the basis for the government's claims of necessity as a basis for curtailing civil liberty. ... The laws will thus not be silent in time of war, but they will speak with a somewhat different voice.\"\n\nIn 2004, [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Antonin Scalia]] used this phrase to decry the plurality decision in ''[[Hamdi v. Rumsfeld]]'' which, in his view, upheld the detention of a [[Citizenship of the United States|US citizen]] as an enemy combatant without charge or suspension of ''habeas corpus''.\n{{quote|Many think it not only inevitable but entirely proper that liberty give way to security in times of national crisis that, at the extremes of military exigency, ''inter arma silent leges''. Whatever the general merits of the view that war silences law or modulates its voice, that view has no place in the interpretation and application of a Constitution designed precisely to confront war and, in a manner that accords with democratic principles, to accommodate it.<ref>Antonin Scalia, [https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/03-6696.ZD.html dissenting opinion] in Hamdi v. Rumsfeld (2004).</ref>}}\n\n== In fiction ==\n\nThe phrase was used as the title for [[Inter Arma Enim Silent Leges (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|a 1999 episode]] of the science fiction TV series ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]''. In it, the character [[List_of_recurring_Star_Trek:_Deep_Space_Nine_characters#Ross,_William_J.|Admiral Ross]] uses the phrase to justify an unethical act of espionage committed during [[Dominion War|a war]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[State of emergency]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/milo.shtml Cicero Pro Milone], at [[The Latin Library]]\n*[https://www.wired.com/news/politics/0,1283,47051,00.html Declan McCullogh, \"Why Liberty Suffers in Wartime\"], 24 September 2001\n*[http://www.suburbanchicagonews.com/focus/terrorism/archives/0901/e30civil.html Jerry Schwartz, AP, \"Will the law be silent in a time of crisis?\"] 30 September 2001\n\n[[Category:Brocards]]\n[[Category:Cicero]]\n[[Category:Latin political words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Chkiss", "label": "safe", "comment": "put punctuation in American style to match the rest of the sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter_arma_enim_silent_leges"}
{"title_page": "List of In Another World with My Smartphone volumes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''In Another World with My Smartphone'' volumes}}\n''[[In Another World with My Smartphone]]'' is a Japanese light novel series written by Patora Fuyuhara and illustrated by [[Eiji Usatsuka]]. It began as a web novel on [[Sh\u014dsetsuka ni Nar\u014d]] website since April 8, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncode.syosetu.com/n1443bp/|title=\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306f\u30b9\u30de\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30f3\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3002|website=ncode.syosetu.com|language=ja|access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> The series was later published by [[Hobby Japan]] beginning on May 22, 2015; nineteen volumes have been published as of December 21, 2019. It is illustrated by Eiji Usatsuka. [[J-Novel Club]] licensed the novel for a digital release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-16/j-novel-club-licenses-in-another-world-with-my-smartphone-novel/.112354|title=J-Novel Club Licenses In Another World with My Smartphone Novel|website=Anime News Network|date=February 16, 2017|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref> At [[Anime Expo]] on July 5, 2018, J-Novel Club announced that the series would be published in print with [[Ingram Content Group|Ingram Publisher Services]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-05/j-novel-club-announces-print-publishing-line-with-in-another-world-with-my-smartphone-novels/.133845 |title=J-Novel Club Announces Print Publishing Line With In Another World with My Smartphone Novels |last=Ressler |first=Karen |date=July 5, 2018 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=July 5, 2018 }}</ref> The novel series was adapted into a manga series by Soto began serialization in the January 2017 issue of [[Comp Ace]] (published November 2016),<ref>{{cite web|title=\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30a8\u30fc\u30b9 2017\u5e741\u6708\u53f7|url=https://web-ace.jp/compace/backnumber/detail/65/|website=\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30a8\u30fc\u30b9|publisher=Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30a8\u30fc\u30b9 2017\u5e741\u6708\u53f7|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B01N3OH390|website=Amazon Japan|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref> with the first two compiled [[tank\u014dbon]] volumes released consecutively in June and July 2017 and the third volume in February 2018.<ref name=\"Manga Vol 1\" /><ref name=\"Manga Vol 2\" /><ref name=\"Manga Vol 3\" />\n__TOC__\n\n==Light novel==\n{{Graphic novel list/header\n| Language        = Japanese\n| SecondLanguage  = English\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n| VolumeNumber = 1\n| OriginalRelDate = May 22, 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hobbyjapan.co.jp/hjnovels/lineup/detail/11.html|title=\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306f\u30b9\u30de\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30f3\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3002\uff11|publisher=[[Hobby Japan]] |work=[[HJ Novels]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n| OriginalISBN = 978-4-79-861018-4\n| LicensedRelDate = March 23, 2017 (E-book)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B06XBJKYS7|title=In Another World with My Smartphone: Volume 1 (E-book)|publisher=[[Amazon (company)|amazon]]|accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref><br/>February 5, 2019 (print)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1718350007|title=In Another World with My Smartphone: Volume 1 (print)|publisher=[[Amazon (company)|amazon]]|accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| ChapterListCol1 =\n* Prologue\n* Chapter I: {{Nihongo|\"In Another World\"|\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306b\u7acb\u3064|Isekai ni Tatsu}}\n* Chapter II: {{Nihongo|\"The More The Merrier! Double the Joy, Half the Sorrow\"|\u65c5\u306f\u9053\u9023\u308c\u3001\u4e16\u306f\u60c5\u3051|Tabi wa Michizure, Yo wa Nasake}}\n* Chapter III: {{Nihongo|\"The Crystal Creature\"|\u6c34\u6676\u306e\u602a\u7269|Suish\u014d no Kaibutsu}}\n| ChapterListCol2 =\n* Chapter IV: {{Nihongo|\"The Royal Family\"|\u738b\u5bb6\u306e\u4e