OKAWA\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|publisher=Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN    = 978-4-04-107165-6\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 5\n | OriginalRelDate = November 24, 2018<ref>{{cite web|title=\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306f\u30b9\u30de\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30f3\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3002(5)|url=https://www.kadokawa.co.jp/product/321808000520/|website=KADOKAWA\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|publisher=Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN    = 978-4-04-107165-6\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 6\n | OriginalRelDate = May 24, 2019<ref>{{cite web|title=\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306f\u30b9\u30de\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30f3\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3002(6)|url=https://www.kadokawa.co.jp/product/321901000404/|website=KADOKAWA\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|publisher=Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN    = 978-4-04-108228-7\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n | VolumeNumber    = 7\n | OriginalRelDate = January 23, 2020<ref>{{cite web|title=\u7570\u4e16\u754c\u306f\u30b9\u30de\u30fc\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30f3\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3002(7)|url=https://www.kadokawa.co.jp/product/321909000437/|website=KADOKAWA\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|publisher=Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n | OriginalISBN    = 978-4-04-109034-3\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list/footer}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Ann|light novel|19379|In Another World with My Smartphone}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of light novels|In Another World with My Smartphone]]\n[[Category:Lists of manga volumes and chapters|In Another World with My Smartphone]]\n", "name_user": "Pazio Paz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLight novel", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_In_Another_World_with_My_Smartphone_volumes"}
{"title_page": "Frank Moffat", "text_new": "{{Full citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Frank Moffat\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Frank J. C. Moffat\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = 1894\n| birth_place = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date =  1978\n| death_place = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = [[Wing (rugby union)|Wing]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Watsonian FC|Watsonians]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints = \n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs = Frank Moffat's XV\n| ru_coachyears = -\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = 1931<br/>1932\n| ru_refereecomps = [[Scottish District rugby structure|Scottish Districts]]<br/>[[1932 Home Nations Championship|Home Nations]]\n| ru_refereeapps = <br/>1\n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = [[George Watson's College]]\n| university = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 1952\n   | term_end      = 1953\n   | predecessor        = [[Dan Drysdale]]\n   | successor          = [[Malcolm Allan]]\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 66th\n }}\n}}\n'''Lt. Col. Frank Moffat''' (1894-1978) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[rugby union]] player. He became an international referee and the 66th [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scotland/rugby/player/3932.html|title=F.J.C. Moffat|website=ESPN scrum}}</ref> He had a distinguished military career with the Gordon Highlanders in the First World War.\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nHe played for [[Watsonian FC|Watsonians]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000578%252f19780331%252f410%252f0025&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref> He scored 47 tries in club rugby in the 1920\u201321 season.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000470%252f19520603%252f200%252f0006&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe refereed the [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]] versus South Africa match in 1931.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugby-memorabilia.co.uk/1931glasgowvssouthafrica.html|title=Rugby Memorabilia Society|website=www.rugby-memorabilia.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was an international referee. He refereed the Wales versus England match in the [[1932 Home Nations Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/match/19436.html|title=Wales v England|website=ESPN scrum}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\n\nHe organised his own representative side, the Frank Moffat XV. His side would play Watsonians every year around New Year. He very often picked players from north-east Scotland in his team. His side accrued a lot of status and the Frank Moffat XV versus Watsonians match was almost treated as another trial match by the Scotland selectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19381228%252f148%252f0007&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000577%252f19371220%252f046%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000540%252f19390103%252f278%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nDuring the Second World War Moffat was the convenor of the Scottish Commnad Rugby Football Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19430130%252f079%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the SRU selection committee for many years.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nHe was Vice-President of the SRU in 1951.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19511030%252f095%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19510526%252f074%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1952 to 1953.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19520524%252f077%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n\nHe was a Lieutenant Colonel of the Gordon Highlanders and a member of the Royal Company of Archers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nMoffat won the Distinguished Service Order in 1917 for his service with the 8/10th battalion in the Battle of Ypres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-press-and-journal-aberdeen-and-aberdeenshire/20190326/281663961356264|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref>\n\nThe citation reads:<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=http://marchmontstgiles.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Nov-insert-Frank-Moffat.pdf |title=Bio |website=marchmontstgiles.org.uk |format=PDF|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nFor conspicuous gallantry and devotion to duty in an attack. He was in command of the right attacking company, which was opposed to a powerful system of the enemy\u2019s defences. He led his company forward with the greatest courage and determination under heavy fire, but they were eventually held up by a machine-gun firing from a concrete emplacement. This he attacked single-handed, putting all the team out of action. He was badly wounded during this encounter, but, inspiring his men to further efforts, he led them several hundred yards further before he fell exhausted. His splendid courage and determination were undoubtedly responsible for the success of the attack.\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Gordon Highlanders Museum in Aberdeen features the 'Moffat Trench' - a replica First World War trench - which is named after him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gordonhighlanders.com/museum/|title=Museum &#124; Gordon Highlanders Museum}}</ref>\n\nAs an archer Moffat won the Montrose Silver Arrow competition twice; in 1954 and in 1959 after a play-off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0001970%252f19590625%252f061%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Outside of rugby union and military==\n\nHe studied medicine at Edinburgh University but as war broke in 1914 he joined the Gordon Highlanders and never returned to medicine.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nHe played cricket for Watsonians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000563%252f19200802%252f082%252f0007&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was a mining engineer by trade. In 1947 he was appointed Estates Mining Engineer for the Scottish division of the National Coal Board.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe died in hospital in 1978 after a stroke. His death was at the end of March that year.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moffat, Frank}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Scottish Districts referees]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union referees]]\n[[Category:Watsonians RFC players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Full citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Frank Moffat\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Frank J. C. Moffat\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = 1894\n| birth_place = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date =  1978\n| death_place = [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = [[Wing (rugby union)|Wing]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Watsonian FC|Watsonians]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = \n| ru_nationalyears = \n| ru_nationalcaps = \n| ru_nationalpoints = \n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs = Frank Moffat's XV\n| ru_coachyears = -\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = 1931<br/>1932\n| ru_refereecomps = [[Scottish District rugby structure|Scottish Districts]]<br/>[[1932 Home Nations Championship|Home Nations]]\n| ru_refereeapps = <br/>1\n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = [[George Watson's College]]\n| university = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 1952\n   | term_end      = 1953\n   | predecessor        = [[Dan Drysdale]]\n   | successor          = [[Malcolm Allan]]\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 66th\n }}\n}}\n'''Lt. Col. Frank Moffat''' (1894-1978) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[rugby union]] player. He became an international referee and the 66th [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scotland/rugby/player/3932.html|title=F.J.C. Moffat|website=ESPN scrum}}</ref> He had a distinguished military career with the Gordon Highlanders in the First World War.\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nHe played for [[Watsonian FC|Watsonians]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000578%252f19780331%252f410%252f0025&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref> He scored 47 tries in club rugby in the 1920-21 season.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000470%252f19520603%252f200%252f0006&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe refereed the [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]] versus South Africa match in 1931.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugby-memorabilia.co.uk/1931glasgowvssouthafrica.html|title=Rugby Memorabilia Society|website=www.rugby-memorabilia.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was an international referee. He refereed the Wales versus England match in the [[1932 Home Nations Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/match/19436.html|title=Wales v England|website=ESPN scrum}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\n\nHe organised his own representative side, the Frank Moffat XV. His side would play Watsonians every year around New Year. He very often picked players from north-east Scotland in his team. His side accrued a lot of status and the Frank Moffat XV versus Watsonians match was almost treated as another trial match by the Scotland selectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19381228%252f148%252f0007&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000577%252f19371220%252f046%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000540%252f19390103%252f278%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nDuring the Second World War Moffat was the convenor of the Scottish Commnad Rugby Football Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19430130%252f079%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the SRU selection commitee for many years.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nHe was Vice-President of the SRU in 1951.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19511030%252f095%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19510526%252f074%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1952 to 1953.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000564%252f19520524%252f077%252f0005&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n\nHe was a Lieutanent Colonel of the Gordon Highlanders and a member of the Royal Company of Archers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nMoffat won the Distinguished Service Order in 1917 for his service with the 8/10th battalion in the Battle of Ypres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-press-and-journal-aberdeen-and-aberdeenshire/20190326/281663961356264|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref>\n\nThe citation reads:<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=http://marchmontstgiles.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Nov-insert-Frank-Moffat.pdf |title=Bio |website=marchmontstgiles.org.uk |format=PDF|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nFor conspicuous gallantry and devotion to duty in an attack. He was in command of the right attacking company, which was opposed to a powerful system of the enemy\u2019s defences. He led his company forward with the greatest courage and determination under heavy fire, but they were eventually held up by a machine-gun firing from a concrete emplacement. This he attacked single-handed, putting all the team out of action. He was badly wounded during this encounter, but, inspiring his men to further efforts, he led them several hundred yards further before he fell exhausted. His splendid courage and determination were undoubtedly responsible for the success of the attack.\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Gordon Highlanders Museum in Aberdeen features the 'Moffat Trench' - a replica First World War trench - which is named after him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gordonhighlanders.com/museum/|title=Museum &#124; Gordon Highlanders Museum}}</ref>\n\nAs an archer Moffat won the Montrose Silver Arrow competition twice; in 1954 and in 1959 after a play-off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0001970%252f19590625%252f061%252f0004&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Outside of rugby union and military==\n\nHe studied medicine at Edinburgh University but as war broke in 1914 he joined the Gordon Highlanders and never returned to medicine.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nHe played cricket for Watsonians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/account/register?countrykey=0&showgiftvoucherclaimingoptions=false&gift=false&nextpage=%2faccount%2flogin%3freturnurl%3d%252fviewer%252fbl%252f0000563%252f19200802%252f082%252f0007&rememberme=false&cookietracking=false&partnershipkey=0&newsletter=false&offers=false&registerreason=none&showsubscriptionoptions=false&showcouponmessaging=false&showfreetrialmessaging=false&showregisteroptions=false&showloginoptions=false&isonlyupgradeable=false|title=Register &#124; British Newspaper Archive|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nHe was a mining engineer by trade. In 1947 he was appointed Estates Mining Engineer for the Scottish division of the National Coal Board.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe died in hospital in 1978 after a stroke. His death was at the end of March that year.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moffat, Frank}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Scottish Districts referees]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union referees]]\n[[Category:Watsonians RFC players]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1920-21 \u2192 1920\u201321, commitee \u2192 committee, Lieutanent \u2192 Lieutenant", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Moffat"}
{"title_page": "Lauren Wise", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{short description|American epidemiologist}}\n'''Lauren Anne Wise''' is a Canadian-American epidemiologist and  professor of epidemiology at [[Boston University School of Public Health]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Education ==\nLauren Wise graduated from St. George\u2019s High School in Montreal, Canada. She completed a Bachelor of Arts ''magna cum laude'' at [[Bowdoin College]] with a double major in biochemistry and women's studies in 1996. She earned a Master of Science with a concentration in reproductive epidemiology from [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health]] in 2000. She completed a Doctor of Science in epidemiology with a minor in biostatistics from [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health]] in 2004.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bu.edu/slone/files/2014/06/CV_Wise.pdf|title=CV|website=Boston University}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{external links|date=January 2020}}\nLauren Wise is a reproductive and perinatal epidemiologist by training. She has been on faculty at the Boston University School of Public Health (BUSPH) since 2004. In 2015, she was promoted to Full Professor in the Department of Epidemiology at BUSPH.  Her research involves the study of environmental and genetic determinants of benign gynecologic disorders, subfertility, and adverse pregnancy outcomes. She is currently Principal Investigator of Pregnancy Study Online (PRESTO), a NICHD-funded North American preconception cohort study of more than 12,000 women and 3,000 of their male partners in which recruitment and follow-up occur via the internet (http://presto.bu.edu). She is also Principal Investigator of NIEHS-funded studies of uterine leiomyomata (fibroids) in the Study of Environment, Lifestyle and Fibroids (SELF), a prospective cohort study of 1,693 young African American women from Detroit, Michigan (http://www.detroitself.org/). She teaches two graduate-level courses (Design and Conduct of Cohort Studies; Reproductive Epidemiology).  She is a Statistical Editor for Human Reproduction, and Associate Editor for the American Journal of Epidemiology and Perinatal and Pediatric Epidemiology. From 2013-2015, she served as Member-At-Large of the Society for Epidemiologic Research (SER). From 2015-2018, she served as Secretary/Treasurer of SER. In 2019, she was elected as President-Elect of the Society for Pediatric and Perinatal Epidemiologic Research (SPER).\n\n==NIH Grants==\nLauren has obtained several grants as Principal Investigator from the National Institutes of Health (NIH), including:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n|Institute\n| colspan=\"3\" |Years of Grant\n|-\n|R01\n|HD086742\n|AN INTERNET-BASED PRECONCEPTION  COHORT STUDY IN NORTH AMERICA AND DENMARK\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2016-2021\n|-\n|R01\n|ES028923\n|A PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF AIR  POLLUTION, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2018-2023\n|-\n|R01\n|ES028235\n|ENVIRONMENTAL RISK FACTORS FOR  UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE ULTRASOUND STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2017-2022\n|-\n|R01\n|ES024749\n|ENDOCRINE DISRUPTING CHEMICALS AND  RISK OF UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2015-2020\n|-\n|R01\n|ES029951\n|A PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF  ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMICALS, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2018-2023\n|-\n|R21\n|HD094322\n|FEASIBILITY OF IN-HOME SEMEN  TESTING IN A NORTH AMERICAN PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|-\n|R03\n|HD094117\n|A PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF CERVICAL  DYSPLASIA, CERVICAL SURGERY, AND FERTILITY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|-\n|R03\n|HD090315\n|LIFESTYLE AND PSYCHOSOCIAL  DETERMINANTS OF MALE SUBFERTILITY: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|-\n|R21\n|HD072326\n|FEASIBILITY OF AN INTERNET-BASED  STUDY OF TIME-TO-PREGNANCY IN THE UNITED STATES\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2013-2015\n|-\n|R01\n|HD057966\n|GENETIC ADMIXTURE STUDY OF UTERINE  FIBROIDS IN AFRICAN AMERICAN WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2008-2013\n|-\n|R03\n|HD055211\n|A PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF DIET AND  FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2008-2010\n|-\n|R03\n|HD069602\n|PSYCHOSOCIAL FACTORS AND RISK OF  UTERINE FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2011-2014\n|-\n|R03\n|CA169888\n|ENDOMETRIAL CANCER IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NCI\n|2013-2015\n|}\n\n\n==Publications==\nLauren's most cited first-authored papers are:\n*Wise LA, JR Palmer, BL Harlow, D Spiegelman, EA Stewart, ... Reproductive factors, hormonal contraception, and risk of uterine leiomyomata in African-American women: a prospective study. American journal of epidemiology 159 (2), 113-123, 2004.[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n*Wise LA, S Zierler, N Krieger, BL Harlow. Adult onset of major depressive disorder in relation to early life violent victimisation: a case-control study. The Lancet 358 (9285), 881-887, 2001.[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n*Wise LA, KJ Rothman, EM Mikkelsen, HT S\u00f8rensen, A Riis, EE Hatch. An internet-based prospective study of body size and time-to-pregnancy. Human reproduction 25 (1), 253-264, 2009. [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.bu.edu/sph/profile/lauren-wise/}}\n* {{google scholar id}}\n* {{twitter|laurenannewise}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wise, Lauren}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University faculty]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Women epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{short description|American epidemiologist}}\n'''Lauren Anne Wise''' is a Canadian-American epidemiologist and  professor of epidemiology at [[Boston University School of Public Health]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Education ==\nLauren Wise graduated from St. George\u2019s High School in Montreal, Canada. She completed a Bachelor of Arts ''magna cum laude'' at [[Bowdoin College]] with a double major in biochemistry and women's studies in 1996. She earned a Master of Science with a concentration in reproductive epidemiology from [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health]] in 2000. She completed a Doctor of Science in epidemiology with a minor in biostatistics from [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health]] in 2004.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bu.edu/slone/files/2014/06/CV_Wise.pdf|title=CV|website=Boston University}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{external links|date=January 2020}}\nLauren Wise is a reproductive and perinatal epidemiologist by training. She has been on faculty at the Boston University School of Public Health (BUSPH) since 2004. In 2015, she was promoted to Full Professor in the Department of Epidemiology at BUSPH.  Her research involves the study of environmental and genetic determinants of benign gynecologic disorders, subfertility, and adverse pregnancy outcomes. She is currently Principal Investigator of Pregnancy Study Online (PRESTO), a NICHD-funded North American preconception cohort study of more than 12,000 women and 3,000 of their male partners in which recruitment and follow-up occur via the internet (http://presto.bu.edu). She is also Principal Investigator of NIEHS-funded studies of uterine leiomyomata (fibroids) in the Study of Environment, Lifestyle and Fibroids (SELF), a prospective cohort study of 1,693 young African American women from Detroit, Michigan (http://www.detroitself.org/). She teaches two graduate-level courses (Design and Conduct of Cohort Studies; Reproductive Epidemiology).  She is a Statistical Editor for Human Reproduction, and Associate Editor for the American Journal of Epidemiology and Perinatal and Pediatric Epidemiology. From 2013-2015, she served as Member-At-Large of the Society for Epidemiologic Research (SER). From 2015-2018, she served as Secretary/Treasurer of SER. In 2019, she was elected as President-Elect of the Society for Pediatric and Perinatal Epidemiologic Research (SPER).\n\n==NIH Grants==\nLauren has obtained several grants as Principal Investigator from the National Institutes of Health (NIH), including:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\nGrant number\tTitle\t Institute\tYears of Grant\nR01\tHD086742\tAN INTERNET-BASED PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY IN NORTH AMERICA AND DENMARK\tNICHD\t2016-2021\nR01\tES028923\tA PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF AIR POLLUTION, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\tNIEHS\t2018-2023\nR01\tES028235\tENVIRONMENTAL RISK FACTORS FOR UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE ULTRASOUND STUDY\tNIEHS\t2017-2022\nR01\tES024749\tENDOCRINE DISRUPTING CHEMICALS AND RISK OF UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\tNIEHS\t2015-2020\nR01\tES029951\tA PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMICALS, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\tNIEHS\t2018-2023\nR21\tHD094322\tFEASIBILITY OF IN-HOME SEMEN TESTING IN A NORTH AMERICAN PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY\tNICHD\t2017-2020\nR03\tHD094117\tA PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF CERVICAL DYSPLASIA, CERVICAL SURGERY, AND FERTILITY\tNICHD\t2017-2020\nR03\tHD090315\tLIFESTYLE AND PSYCHOSOCIAL DETERMINANTS OF MALE SUBFERTILITY: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\tNICHD\t2017-2020\nR21\tHD072326\tFEASIBILITY OF AN INTERNET-BASED STUDY OF TIME-TO-PREGNANCY IN THE UNITED STATES\tNICHD\t2013-2015\nR01\tHD057966\tGENETIC ADMIXTURE STUDY OF UTERINE FIBROIDS IN AFRICAN AMERICAN WOMEN\tNICHD\t2008-2013\nR03\tHD055211\tA PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF DIET AND FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\tNICHD\t2008-2010\nR03\tHD069602\tPSYCHOSOCIAL FACTORS AND RISK OF UTERINE FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\tNICHD\t2011-2014\nR03\tCA169888\tENDOMETRIAL CANCER IN BLACK WOMEN\tNCI\t2013-2015\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"2\" |Grant number\n|Title\n|Institute\n| colspan=\"3\" |Years of Grant\n|-\n|R01\n|HD086742\n|AN INTERNET-BASED PRECONCEPTION  COHORT STUDY IN NORTH AMERICA AND DENMARK\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2016-2021\n|\n|-\n|R01\n|ES028923\n|A PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF AIR  POLLUTION, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2018-2023\n|\n|-\n|R01\n|ES028235\n|ENVIRONMENTAL RISK FACTORS FOR  UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE ULTRASOUND STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2017-2022\n|\n|-\n|R01\n|ES024749\n|ENDOCRINE DISRUPTING CHEMICALS AND  RISK OF UTERINE FIBROIDS: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2015-2020\n|\n|-\n|R01\n|ES029951\n|A PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY OF  ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMICALS, FERTILITY, AND MISCARRIAGE\n| colspan=\"2\" |NIEHS\n|2018-2023\n|\n|-\n|R21\n|HD094322\n|FEASIBILITY OF IN-HOME SEMEN  TESTING IN A NORTH AMERICAN PRECONCEPTION COHORT STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|\n|-\n|R03\n|HD094117\n|A PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF CERVICAL  DYSPLASIA, CERVICAL SURGERY, AND FERTILITY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|\n|-\n|R03\n|HD090315\n|LIFESTYLE AND PSYCHOSOCIAL  DETERMINANTS OF MALE SUBFERTILITY: A PROSPECTIVE STUDY\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2017-2020\n|\n|-\n|R21\n|HD072326\n|FEASIBILITY OF AN INTERNET-BASED  STUDY OF TIME-TO-PREGNANCY IN THE UNITED STATES\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2013-2015\n|\n|-\n|R01\n|HD057966\n|GENETIC ADMIXTURE STUDY OF UTERINE  FIBROIDS IN AFRICAN AMERICAN WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2008-2013\n|\n|-\n|R03\n|HD055211\n|A PROSPECTIVE STUDY OF DIET AND  FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2008-2010\n|\n|-\n|R03\n|HD069602\n|PSYCHOSOCIAL FACTORS AND RISK OF  UTERINE FIBROIDS IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NICHD\n|2011-2014\n|\n|-\n|R03\n|CA169888\n|ENDOMETRIAL CANCER IN BLACK WOMEN\n| colspan=\"2\" |NCI\n|2013-2015\n|\n|}\n\n\n==Publications==\nLauren's most cited first-authored papers are:\n*Wise LA, JR Palmer, BL Harlow, D Spiegelman, EA Stewart, ... Reproductive factors, hormonal contraception, and risk of uterine leiomyomata in African-American women: a prospective study. American journal of epidemiology 159 (2), 113-123, 2004.[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n*Wise LA, S Zierler, N Krieger, BL Harlow. Adult onset of major depressive disorder in relation to early life violent victimisation: a case-control study. The Lancet 358 (9285), 881-887, 2001.[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n*Wise LA, KJ Rothman, EM Mikkelsen, HT S\u00f8rensen, A Riis, EE Hatch. An internet-based prospective study of body size and time-to-pregnancy. Human reproduction 25 (1), 253-264, 2009. [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=pEGENLUAAAAJ]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.bu.edu/sph/profile/lauren-wise/}}\n* {{google scholar id}}\n* {{twitter|laurenannewise}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wise, Lauren}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University faculty]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Women epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Wiselauren", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNIH Grants", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Wise"}
{"title_page": "Sue Hickey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder | \n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name= Sue Hickey\n| honorific-suffix = [[Tasmanian House of Assembly|MP]]\n| image=\n| caption=\n| nationality= [[Australian]]\n| order = 34th\n| office = Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly\n| term_start= 1 May 2018\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Mark Shelton]]\n| successor =\n| order1 = 68th\n| office1 = Lord Mayor of Hobart\n| term_start1 = 5 November 2014\n| term_end1 =21 March 2018\n| deputy1 =Ron Christie\n| predecessor1 =[[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]]\n| successor1 = Ron Christie\n| office2 = Member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] for [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]]\n| term_start2 = 3 March 2018\n| term_end2 = 28 September 2018\n| office3 = Member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] for [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]\n| term_start3 = 28 September 2018\n| term_end3 = \n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1958|7|25}}\n| birth_place=[[Hobart]], Tasmania, Australia\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=\n| party= [[Liberal Party of Australia (Tasmanian Division)|Liberal]]\n}}\n'''Susanne Lynnette Hickey''' (born 25 July 1958) is an [[Australia]]n politician. She has been a [[Liberal Party of Australia (Tasmanian Division)|Liberal Party]] member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] since the [[2018 Tasmanian state election|2018 election]], representing the electorate of [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]] (now called [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]). She was previously [[Lord Mayor of Hobart]] from 2014 until 2018.<ref name=mercury> {{cite news|last1=Howard |first1=Jessica| title=Sue Hickey\u2019s successful rise to Lord Mayor of Hobart|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/sue-hickeys-successful-rise-to-lord-mayor-of-hobart/story-fnj4f7k1-1227108873427|publisher=The Mercury (Hobart)|date=1 November 2014|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHickey has been [[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]] since May 2018. She unexpectedly won the Speaker position with the support of the opposition Labor and Greens parties over Liberal nominee [[Rene Hidding]], and has stated that she will not attend Liberal Party meetings and will \"mostly\" vote with the Government, but will assess bills \"on their merit\".<ref name=speaker>{{cite news|last1=Burgess |first1=Georgie|title=New Speaker Sue Hickey distances herself from Liberal Party in dramatic first day of Parliament|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-01/sue-hickey-set-to-become-new-tasmanian-speaker-in-surprise-move/9714572|accessdate=2018-05-01|work=ABC News| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Coulter |first1=Ellen |last2=Dunlevie |first2=James|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-04/sue-hickey-new-tasmanian-parliamentary-speaker/9723632 | title=Sue Hickey: A Tasmanian Liberal, but not as you know it | work=ABC News | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation| date=2018-05-04 | accessdate=2018-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHickey first entered public life when she won the [[Miss Tasmania Quest]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.archives.tas.gov.au/default.aspx?detail=1&type=I&id=NS3428/1/25|title=Photograph - Sue Hickey, Miss Tasmania 1979|publisher=Tasmanian Archive and Heritage Office|date=June 2012|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> She was also a television weather girl on [[TVT (TV station)|TVT6]] for many years.<ref name=mercury/> She later worked in a number of retail and service positions, before starting a career in marketing. In 1991, she established her own marketing business, Slick Promotions.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=http://www.slickpromotions.com.au/aboutus.aspx |publisher=Slick Promotions |accessdate=2020-01-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930051549/http://www.slickpromotions.com.au/aboutus.aspx |archivedate=2013-09-30}}</ref>  Hickey won the Tasmanian Businesswoman of the Year award in 2007.<ref name=mercury/> Hickey obtained an [[MBA]] from the [[University of Tasmania]] in 2012 whilst running her own business, being an Alderman on the Hobart City Council and being President of the Rotary Club of Hobart.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hickey |first1=Sue |title=Sue Hickey stands for Lord Mayor of Hobart |url=http://tasmaniantimes.com/index.php?/pr-article/sue-hickey-stands-for-lord-mayor-of-hobart/ |accessdate=2020-01-15 |work=Tasmanian Times |date=2014-08-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030053353/http://tasmaniantimes.com/index.php?/pr-article/sue-hickey-stands-for-lord-mayor-of-hobart/ |archivedate=2014-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Mayor of Hobart==\nShe was a successful candidate for the Hobart City Council in the 2011 Tasmanian local government elections, elected as Alderman.\n\nHickey defeated incumbent Lord Mayor [[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]] at the 2014 local government elections, serving as the Right Honourable, The Lord Mayor of Hobart, Alderman Sue Hickey until her election to State Parliament.<ref name=\"abc-elect-win\">{{cite web|title=Local council polls: Sue Hickey elected Hobart Lord Mayor over Damon Thomas|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-10-29/sue-hickey-elected-as-hobart-next-lord-mayor/5850642|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==State MP==\nIn 2018, Hickey ran successfully as a Liberal candidate for [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]] (now [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]) in the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]].\n\nOn 1 May 2018, at the first sitting of the House of Assembly after the election, Labor leader [[Rebecca White]] nominated Hickey as [[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly|Speaker]], in competition with the Liberal Party's preferred candidate, [[Rene Hidding]]. Hickey was elected Speaker with the support of Labor and the Greens.<ref name=speaker/> She immediately distanced herself from the Liberal Party, revealing she would vote independently on government bills, although she said she would \"always support the Liberal Government\" on [[confidence and supply]].<ref name=Hickey1>{{cite news|last1=Coulter |first1=Ellen |last2=Whitson |first2=Rhiana|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-21/sue-hickey-breaks-ranks-over-glenorchy-council-loan/9784128|title=Speaker Sue Hickey departs from Liberal script to call for Glenorchy Council's rescue|accessdate=2020-01-15|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=2018-05-22}}</ref> In some instances, Hickey has deprived the Liberal Party of its 13-12 majority in the Assembly.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.suehickey.com.au/ Sue Hickey \u2013 electoral website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Mayor of Hobart]]\n|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=Ron Christie}}\n{{s-par|au-tas}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Shelton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TasCurrentMHAs}}\n{{Presiding officers of Australian legislatures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hickey, Sue}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors and Lord Mayors of Hobart]]\n[[Category:Australian city councillors]]\n[[Category:Australian women in business]]\n[[Category:University of Tasmania alumni]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder | \n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name= Sue Hickey\n| honorific-suffix = [[Tasmanian House of Assembly|MP]]\n| image=\n| caption=\n| nationality= [[Australian]]\n| order = 34th\n| office = Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly\n| term_start= 1 May 2018\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Mark Shelton]]\n| successor =\n| order1 = 68th\n| office1 = Lord Mayor of Hobart\n| term_start1 = 5 November 2014\n| term_end1 =21 March 2018\n| deputy1 =Ron Christie\n| predecessor1 =[[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]]\n| successor1 = Ron Christie\n| office2 = Member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] for [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]]\n| term_start2 = 3 March 2018\n| term_end2 = 28 September 2018\n| office3 = Member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] for [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]\n| term_start3 = 28 September 2018\n| term_end3 = \n| birth_date= {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1958|7|25}}\n| birth_place=[[Hobart]], Tasmania, Australia\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=\n| party= [[Liberal Party of Australia (Tasmanian Division)|Liberal]]\n}}\n'''Susanne Lynnette Hickey''' (born 25 July 1958) is an [[Australia]]n politician. She has been a [[Liberal Party of Australia (Tasmanian Division)|Liberal Party]] member of the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]] since the [[2018 Tasmanian state election|2018 election]], representing the electorate of [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]] (now called [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]). She was previously [[Lord Mayor of Hobart]] from 2014 until 2018.<ref name=mercury> {{cite news|last1=Howard |first1=Jessica| title=Sue Hickey\u2019s successful rise to Lord Mayor of Hobart|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/sue-hickeys-successful-rise-to-lord-mayor-of-hobart/story-fnj4f7k1-1227108873427|publisher=The Mercury (Hobart)|date=1 November 2014|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHickey has been [[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]] since May 2018. She unexpectedly won the Speaker position with the support of the opposition Labor and Greens parties over Liberal nominee [[Rene Hidding]], and has stated that she will not attend Liberal Party meetings and will \"mostly\" vote with the Government, but will assess bills \"on their merit\".<ref name=speaker>{{cite news|last1=Burgess |first1=Georgie|title=New Speaker Sue Hickey distances herself from Liberal Party in dramatic first day of Parliament|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-01/sue-hickey-set-to-become-new-tasmanian-speaker-in-surprise-move/9714572|accessdate=2018-05-01|work=ABC News| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Coulter |first1=Ellen |last2=Dunlevie |first2=James|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-04/sue-hickey-new-tasmanian-parliamentary-speaker/9723632 | title=Sue Hickey: A Tasmanian Liberal, but not as you know it | work=ABC News | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation| date=2018-05-04 | accessdate=2018-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHickey first entered public life when she won the [[Miss Tasmania Quest]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.archives.tas.gov.au/default.aspx?detail=1&type=I&id=NS3428/1/25|title=Photograph - Sue Hickey, Miss Tasmania 1979|publisher=Tasmanian Archive and Heritage Office|date=June 2012|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> She was also a television weather girl on [[TVT (TV station)|TVT6]] for many years.<ref name=mercury/> She later worked in a number of retail and service positions, before starting a career in marketing. In 1991, she established her own marketing business, Slick Promotions.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=http://www.slickpromotions.com.au/aboutus.aspx |publisher=Slick Promotions |accessdate=2020-01-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930051549/http://www.slickpromotions.com.au/aboutus.aspx |archivedate=2013-09-30}}</ref>  Hickey won the Tasmanian Businesswoman of the Year award in 2007.<ref name=mercury/> Hickey obtained an [[MBA]] from the [[University of Tasmania]] in 2012 whilst running her own business, being an Alderman on the Hobart City Council and being President of the Rotary Club of Hobart.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hickey |first1=Sue |title=Sue Hickey stands for Lord Mayor of Hobart |url=http://tasmaniantimes.com/index.php?/pr-article/sue-hickey-stands-for-lord-mayor-of-hobart/ |accessdate=2020-01-15 |work=Tasmanian Times |date=2014-08-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030053353/http://tasmaniantimes.com/index.php?/pr-article/sue-hickey-stands-for-lord-mayor-of-hobart/ |archivedate=2014-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Mayor of Hobart==\nShe was a successful candidate for the Hobart City Council in the 2011 Tasmanian local government elections, elected as Alderman.\n\nHickey defeated incumbent Lord Mayor [[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]] at the 2014 local government elections, serving as the Right Honourable, The Lord Mayor of Hobart, Alderman Sue Hickey until her election to State Parliament.<ref name=\"abc-elect-win\">{{cite web|title=Local council polls: Sue Hickey elected Hobart Lord Mayor over Damon Thomas|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-10-29/sue-hickey-elected-as-hobart-next-lord-mayor/5850642|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==State MP==\nIn 2018, Hickey ran successfully as a Liberal candidate for [[Division of Denison (state)|Denison]] (now [[Division of Clark (state)|Clark]]) in the [[Tasmanian House of Assembly]].\n\nOn 1 May 2018, at the first sitting of the House of Assembly after the election, Labor leader [[Rebecca White]] nominated Hickey as [[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly|Speaker]], in competition with the Liberal Party's preferred candidate, [[Rene Hidding]]. Hickey was elected Speaker with the support of Labor and the Greens.<ref name=speaker/> She immediately distanced herself from the Liberal Party, revealing she would vote independently on government bills, although she said she would \"always support the Liberal Government\" on [[confidence and supply]].<ref name=Hickey1>{{cite news|last1=Coulter |first1=Ellen |last2=Whitson |first2=Rhiana|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-21/sue-hickey-breaks-ranks-over-glenorchy-council-loan/9784128|title=Speaker Sue Hickey departs from Liberal script to call for Glenorchy Council's rescue|accessdate=2020-01-15|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=2018-05-22}}</ref> In some instances, Hickey has deprived the Liberal Party of its 13-12 majority in the Assembly, voting against bills on merit rather than party dictates.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.suehickey.com.au/ Sue Hickey \u2013 electoral website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Damon Thomas (mayor)|Damon Thomas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Mayor of Hobart]]\n|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=Ron Christie}}\n{{s-par|au-tas}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Shelton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{TasCurrentMHAs}}\n{{Presiding officers of Australian legislatures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hickey, Sue}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors and Lord Mayors of Hobart]]\n[[Category:Australian city councillors]]\n[[Category:Australian women in business]]\n[[Category:University of Tasmania alumni]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tasmanian House of Assembly]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "1199bob", "label": "safe", "comment": "deleting original commentary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sue_Hickey"}
{"title_page": "EnCase", "text_new": "{{redirect|Encase|the coil|encased coil|the meaning of encase|wikt:encase}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = EnCase\n| logo = [[File:EnCase logo.jpg|200px|alt=EnCase Forensic Logo]]\n| screenshot = [[File:Encase.png|200px|alt=Blank EnCase project file]]\n| caption = Blank EnCase (V6.16.1) project file\n| developer = [http://www.guidancesoftware.com Guidance Software]\n[http://www.opentext.com OpenText]\n| released = 1998\n| latest release version = 8.10\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|26}}\n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| status = Active\n| genre = [[Computer forensics]]\n| website = [http://www.guidancesoftware.com www.guidancesoftware.com]\n[http://www.opentext.com\nwww.opentext.com]\n}}\n'''EnCase''' is the shared technology within a suite of digital investigations products by [[Guidance Software]] (now acquired by OpenText). The software comes in several products designed for [[forensic]], [[cyber security]], [[security analytics]], and [[e-discovery]] use. Encase is traditionally used in forensics to recover evidence from seized hard drives. Encase allows the investigator to conduct in depth analysis of user files to collect evidence such as documents, pictures, internet history and Windows Registry information.\n\nThe company also offers EnCase training and certification.\n\nData recovered by EnCase has been used in various court systems, such as in the cases of the [[Dennis_Rader#Arrest|BTK Killer]] and the [[murder of Danielle van Dam]].<ref name=\"UK Court Usage\"/><ref>Dillon, Jeff, and Steve Perez. [http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/danielle/20020703-9999-noon.html \"Prosecutor hammers away at computer forensic expert; Dad's patron describes Brenda's propositions,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714112541/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/danielle/20020703-9999-noon.html |date=2014-07-14 }} San Diego Union-Tribune, July 3, 2002.</ref> Additional EnCase forensic work was documented in other cases such as the evidence provided for the Casey Anthony, Unabomber, and Mucko (Wakefield Massacre) cases.\n\n<br />\n\n== Company and Product Overview ==\nEnCase was originally created by Shawn McCreight the founder of Guidance Software in 1997 out of his home. In 1998 EnCase Forensic officially released (originally named Expert Witness for Windows). At the time there were no GUI forensic tools available.\n\nIn 2002 EnCase Enterprise was released allowing the first network enabled digital forensic tool to be used in forensic, investigative, and security matters.\n\nIn 2005 EnCase eDiscovery was released which further enabled the network abilities of EnCase to allow Identification, Collection, Preservation, and Analysis of ESI for Litigation and Investigative purposes.\n\nIn 2007 EnCase AIRS (Automated Incident Response Suite) was released (now discontinued and evolved to EnCase Endpoint Security) to automate the scanning, documenting, and remediation abilities of EnCase Enterprise. Also in 2007 was the release of EnCase Information Assurance, EnCase Data Audit and Policy Enforcement (both also effectively integrated into EnCase Endpoint Security).\n\nIn 2008 EnCase Cybersecurity was released which combined many of the tools and automation from previous security functions an streamlined the workflow of incident response.\n\nIn 2015 EnCase Endpoint Security was released which was the evolution of Endpoint Security into a more user friendly web interface as well as further integration with many other security tools to further expedite and shorten the response time from an attack or event.\n\nIn 2016 EnCase Enterprise needed a face lift and the distributed agent (formerly referred to as servlet) was given more abilities with the redesign into EnCase Endpoint Investigator. Also in 2016 the release of EnCase Risk Manager for data risk assessment, audit, DLP-like services, and compliance.\n\nIn 2017 Guidance Software was acquired by [[OpenText]], and the company name \"Guidance Software\" is no longer used.\n\n==EnCase Product Line==\nEnCase technology is available within a number of products, currently including: EnCase Forensic, EnCase Endpoint Investigator, EnCase eDiscovery (which includes EnCase Legal Hold), EnCase Endpoint Security and EnCase Portable.<ref>url=http://www.guidancesoftware.com/\"| 11 October 2012</ref> Guidance Software also runs training courses from Foundations in Computer Forensics, to several expert series courses to include an EnScripting course to automate various functions within EnCase. Further, certification os offered to train toward and prove knowledge within various fields to include EnCE (EnCase Certified Examiner), EnCEP (EnCase Certified eDiscovery Practitioner), CFSR (Certified Forensic Security Responder). The EnCase training team have trained over 100000 individuals to date.<ref>url=\"https://www.sprintzeal.com/\" | 11 October 2012</ref>\n\n==Features==\nEnCase contains tools for several areas of the [[digital forensic process]]; acquisition, analysis and reporting. The software also includes a scripting facility called EnScript with various [[Application programming interface|API's]] for interacting with evidence.\n\n===Expert Witness File Format===\nEnCase contains functionality to [[Digital forensic process#Acquisition|create forensic images]] of suspect media. Images are stored in proprietary ''Expert Witness File'' format; the compressible file format is prefixed with case data information and consists of a [[bit]]-by-bit (i.e. exact) copy of the media inter-spaced with CRC hashes for every 64K of data. The file format also appends an MD5 hash of the entire drive as a footer.<ref name=\"advancesdf\" />\n\n===Mobile forensics===\nAs of EnCase V7, Mobile Phone Analysis is possible with the addition some add-ons available from Guidance Software.<ref>{{Cite web|last=GuidanceSoftware|title=EnCase Forensic V7|url=http://www.guidancesoftware.com/forensic.htm|work=GuidanceSoftware|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em|refs=\n<ref name=\"advancesdf\" >{{Cite book|title=Advances in digital forensics II|year=2006|publisher=Springer|isbn=0-387-36890-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jr2PPjwXJQwC|editor=Martin S. Olivier, Sujeet Shenoi|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"UK Court Usage\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/05/technology/techspecial4/05forensic.html?_r=1&ref=techspecial4\n|title=Deleting may be easy, but your hard drive still tells all\n|publisher=[[The New York Times|New York Times]]\n|accessdate=2009-01-11\n| first=Eric A.\n| last=Taub\n| date=2006-04-05}}</ref>}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite web|last=Garber|first=Lee|title=EnCase: A Case Study in Computer-Forensic Technology|url=http://www.cosgrovecomputer.com/documents/computer_magazine_article.pdf|publisher=IEEE Computer Society|accessdate=10 November 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://darkhunts.com/image-forensics-collect-evidence-from-images/ Digital Forensics Tutorials]\n\n{{Digital forensics}}\n\n[[Category:Law enforcement equipment]]\n[[Category:Hard disk software]]\n[[Category:Computer forensics]]\n[[Category:Digital forensics software]]\n[[Category:Computer security]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Encase|the coil|encased coil|the meaning of encase|wikt:encase}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = EnCase\n| logo = [[File:EnCase logo.jpg|200px|alt=EnCase Forensic Logo]]\n| screenshot = [[File:Encase.png|200px|alt=Blank EnCase project file]]\n| caption = Blank EnCase (V6.16.1) project file\n| developer = [http://www.guidancesoftware.com Guidance Software]\n[http://www.opentext.com OpenText]\n| released = 1998\n| latest release version = 8.10\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|26}}\n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| status = Active\n| genre = [[Computer forensics]]\n| website = [http://www.guidancesoftware.com www.guidancesoftware.com]\n[http://www.opentext.com\nwww.opentext.com]\n}}\n'''EnCase''' is the shared technology within a suite of digital investigations products by [[Guidance Software]] (now acquired by OpenText). The software comes in several products designed for [[forensic]], [[cyber security]], [[security analytics]], and [[e-discovery]] use. Encase is traditionally used in forensics to recover evidence from seized hard drives. Encase allows the investigator to conduct in depth analysis of user files to collect evidence such as documents, pictures, internet history and Windows Registry information.\n\nThe company also offers EnCase training and certification.\n\nData recovered by EnCase has been used in various court systems, such as in the cases of the [[Dennis_Rader#Arrest|BTK Killer]] and the [[murder of Danielle van Dam]].<ref name=\"UK Court Usage\"/><ref>Dillon, Jeff, and Steve Perez. [http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/danielle/20020703-9999-noon.html \"Prosecutor hammers away at computer forensic expert; Dad's patron describes Brenda's propositions,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714112541/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/danielle/20020703-9999-noon.html |date=2014-07-14 }} San Diego Union-Tribune, July 3, 2002.</ref> Additional EnCase forensic work was documented in other cases such as the evidence provided for the Casey Anthony, Unabomber, and Mucko (Wakefield Massacre) cases.\n\n<br />\n\n== Company and Product Overview ==\nEnCase was originally created by Shawn McCreight the founder of Guidance Software in 1997 out of his home. In 1998 EnCase Forensic officially released (originally named Expert Witness for Windows). At the time there were no GUI forensic tools available.\n\nIn 2002 EnCase Enterprise was released allowing the first network enabled digital forensic tool to be used in forensic, investigative, and security matters.\n\nIn 2005 EnCase eDiscovery was released which further enabled the network abilities of EnCase to allow Identification, Collection, Preservation, and Analysis of ESI for Litigation and Investigative purposes.\n\nIn 2007 EnCase AIRS (Automated Incident Response Suite) was released (now discontinued and evolved to EnCase Endpoint Security) to automate the scanning, documenting, and remediation abilities of EnCase Enterprise. Also in 2007 was the release of EnCase Information Assurance, EnCase Data Audit and Policy Enforcement (both also effectively integrated into EnCase Endpoint Security).\n\nIn 2008 EnCase Cybersecurity was released which combined many of the tools and automation from previous security functions an streamlined the workflow of incident response.\n\nIn 2015 EnCase Endpoint Security was released which was the evolution of Endpoint Security into a more user friendly web interface as well as further integration with many other security tools to further expedite and shorten the response time from an attack or event.\n\nIn 2016 EnCase Enterprise needed a face lift and the distributed agent (formerly referred to as servlet) was given more abilities with the redesign into EnCase Endpoint Investigator. Also in 2016 the release of EnCase Risk Manager for data risk assessment, audit, DLP-like services, and compliance.\n\nIn 2017 Guidance Software was acquired by [[OpenText]], and the company name \"Guidance Software\" is no longer used.\n\n==EnCase Product Line==\nEnCase technology is available within a number of products, currently including: EnCase Forensic, EnCase Endpoint Investigator, EnCase eDiscovery (which includes EnCase Legal Hold), EnCase Endpoint Security and EnCase Portable.<ref>url=http://www.guidancesoftware.com/\"| 11 October 2012</ref> Guidance Software also runs training courses from Foundations in Computer Forensics, to several expert series courses to include an EnScripting course to automate various functions within EnCase. Further, certification os offered to train toward and prove knowledge within various fields to include EnCE (EnCase Certified Examiner), EnCEP (EnCase Certified eDiscovery Practitioner), CFSR (Certified Forensic Security Responder). The EnCase training team have trained over 100000 individuals to date.<ref>url=\"https://www.sprintzeal.com/\" | 11 October 2012</ref>\n\n==Features==\nEnCase contains tools for several areas of the [[digital forensic process]]; acquisition, analysis and reporting. The software also includes a scripting facility called EnScript with various [[Application programming interface|API's]] for interacting with evidence.\n\n===Expert Witness File Format===\nEnCase contains functionality to [[Digital forensic process#Acquisition|create forensic images]] of suspect media. Images are stored in proprietary ''Expert Witness File'' format; the compressible file format is prefixed with case data information and consists of a [[bit]]-by-bit (i.e. exact) copy of the media inter-spaced with CRC hashes for every 64K of data. The file format also appends an MD5 hash of the entire drive as a footer.<ref name=\"advancesdf\" />\n\n===Mobile forensics===\nAs of EnCase V7, Mobile Phone Analysis is possible with the addition some add-ons available from Guidance Software.<ref>{{Cite web|last=GuidanceSoftware|title=EnCase Forensic V7|url=http://www.guidancesoftware.com/forensic.htm|work=GuidanceSoftware|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em|refs=\n<ref name=\"advancesdf\" >{{Cite book|title=Advances in digital forensics II|year=2006|publisher=Springer|isbn=0-387-36890-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jr2PPjwXJQwC|editor=Martin S. Olivier, Sujeet Shenoi|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"UK Court Usage\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/05/technology/techspecial4/05forensic.html?_r=1&ref=techspecial4\n|title=Deleting may be easy, but your hard drive still tells all\n|publisher=[[The New York Times|New York Times]]\n|accessdate=2009-01-11\n| first=Eric A